TEM images of P1-P9 (Fig. 2
                           ) indicate that the reaction conditions have a significant impact on the particle size and crystallinity of PDs. Table 3
                            presents the TEM results for P1-P9. The average particle size of the products is the mean value obtained after counting 150 particles. For P1, PDs have poor dispersion and aggregate into clusters. The individual PD particles are large and quasi-spherical. The particle size distribution ranges from 14 to 32 nm and the average particle size is 21.85 nm. With regard to P2, as the mass ratio of CA to urea increases, the clustered aggregates of PDs essentially disappear. They appear as spheroidal black spots and their dispersibility significantly improves. The particle size distribution narrows to 4–18 nm, with an average particle size of 11.46 nm. In comparison to P2, PDs in P3 do not exhibit cluster-like aggregates. The spheroidal black dots are more distinct and their dispersibility further increases. The particle size further decreases, with a distribution range of 0.9–8.1 nm and an average particle size of 3.87 nm. For P4, PDs exhibit good monodispersity and are spheroidal. The particle size is relatively large and the particle size distribution ranges from 9 to 21 nm, with an average particle size of 14.72 nm. Compared to P4, PDs in P5 also demonstrate excellent dispersity. However, their particle size is smaller, with a size distribution ranging from 2.1 to 7.2 nm and an average particle size of 4.45 nm. A large number of polymers are present in P6 and PDs are distributed in the polymers. The particle size is larger than that of P5, with a size distribution ranging from 4.4 to 11.3 nm and an average particle size of 8.08 nm. Similar to P6, PDs in P7 are distributed in the polymers and display wonderful dispersity. The particle size ranges from 3 to 11 nm, with an average particle size of 7.28 nm. Regarding P8, PDs exhibit poor dispersibility. The particle size is large, with a distribution ranging from 4.3 to 13.7 nm and an average particle size of 8.8 nm. Compared to P8, PDs in P9 demonstrate monodispersity. They have a narrower particle size distribution range of 4.2–7.7 nm and a smaller average particle size of 5.7 nm.

Using the average particle size of PDs as an indicator, the impact of the initial reaction conditions on this parameter is analyzed by adopting range (R) and variance (Table 4
                           ). By comparing the values of R, it is clear that RB > RC > RA. This indicates that the molar ratio of H2 to O2 has the greatest impact on the average particle size of the products, followed by the mass ratio of CA to urea, and finally the total mass of the precursors. The R values for three factors are greater than that of the error column, manifesting that three factors affect the average particle size of PDs. Fig. 3
                            displays the relationship between the average particle size of PDs and different factors. In detail, the molar ratio of H2 to O2 has the most significant impact on the average particle size of PDs. When the molar ratio of H2 to O2 is 1:1, the average particle size of PDs is the largest. As the molar ratio of H2 to O2 increases, the average particle size of PDs significantly decreases. Additionally, the mass ratio of CA to urea has a remarkable effect on the average particle size of PDs. When the mass ratio of CA to urea is 10:3, the average particle size of PDs is the smallest. As the mass ratio of CA to urea reduces, the average particle size of PDs gradually improves. The total mass of the precursors has a relatively evident impact on the average particle size of PDs. When the total mass of the precursors is at its maximum, the average particle size of PDs is the largest. Therefore, PDs with controllable particle sizes can be prepared by adjusting the reaction conditions, laying the foundation for their application in various fields. To eliminate the influence of errors on the orthogonal experiments, variance analysis results are employed. Specifically, the molar ratio of H2 to O2, the mass ratio of CA to urea, and the total mass of the precursors have significant, influential, and certain effects on the average particle size of PDs, respectively. The ranking of influence magnitude is consistent with the results of the range analysis.
